  "texts": [
    "It can capture basic emotions, but not fine-grained sentiment polarity.",
    "Both sentences \"I am ecstatic\" and \"I am happy\" might be represented similarly, though the intensity differs.• Intentionality vs. Factuality: AMRs will not distinguish between the real events that have occurred and intentions.",
    "For example, for the sentence \"He wants to go\", in the generated AMR, both verbs 'want' and 'go' have the same status, where 'go' may or may not happen.• Semantic Variation: AMRs of two different sentences with the same semantic are not identical.",
    "For the sentences \"He was absent\" and \"He was not present\" two different AMRs are generated.Although AMR was initially designed only for the English language, later attempts were made to generate AMRs for other languages (see Section 5).",
    "AMRs should also be used carefully for syntax other than natural language."
  ],
